<subSubSection box="[199,1310,1447,1473]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,1338,2013]" box="[199,1310,1447,1473]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1447,1473]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet refers to the quite long retrolateral tibial apophysis of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,1338,2013]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1482,1508]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName authority="Martínez &amp; Brescovit &amp; Villarreal &amp; Oliveira, 2021" authorityName="Martínez &amp; Brescovit &amp; Villarreal &amp; Oliveira" authorityYear="2021" box="[436,664,1483,1509]" class="Arachnida" family="Anyphaenidae" genus="Patrera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longitibialis" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[436,664,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Patrera longitibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[672,735,1483,1509]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[672,735,1483,1509]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, can be recognized from those of the remaining species of the genus by their stronger, dome-shape ventral tegular process and by the large retrolateral tibial apophysis, which is as long as the cymbium (
<figureCitation box="[431,533,1555,1583]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="55.[151,250,1875,1899]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,597,1850]" captionTargetId="figure-154@55.[151,1436,597,1852]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURE 29A–E. Patrera longitibialis n. sp. Male (ICN-Ar-5882): A habitus, dorsal view; B left leg, ventral view; C palp, retroventral view; D palp, ventral view; E palp, retrolateral view.Abbreviations: E, embolus; VTP, ventral tegular process. Scale bars: A: B: 1mm; C: 0.5mm; D–E: 0.2mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468447" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468447/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 29B</figureCitation>
̅D).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="55" lastPageNumber="56" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1437,1338,2013]" lastBlockId="55.[151,1436,151,537]" lastPageId="55" lastPageNumber="56" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1590,1616]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[354,412,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Male</emphasis>
(
<typeStatus box="[428,537,1591,1617]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Holotype</typeStatus>
, ICN-Ar-5882). Carapace pale brownish, lightest around the fovea (
<figureCitation box="[1317,1424,1591,1617]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="55.[151,250,1875,1899]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,597,1850]" captionTargetId="figure-154@55.[151,1436,597,1852]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURE 29A–E. Patrera longitibialis n. sp. Male (ICN-Ar-5882): A habitus, dorsal view; B left leg, ventral view; C palp, retroventral view; D palp, ventral view; E palp, retrolateral view.Abbreviations: E, embolus; VTP, ventral tegular process. Scale bars: A: B: 1mm; C: 0.5mm; D–E: 0.2mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468447" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468447/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 29A</figureCitation>
). Chelicerae pale brownish. Labium dark brown with the middle zone lightest, endites pale brownish anteriorly darker in the posterior edges. Sternum pale yellow with a darkest patch on the posterior side. Legs brownish with metatarsi and tarsi darkest than the other segments. Abdomen pale yellow; ventrally darkest from epigastric furrow to tracheal spiracle. Spinnerets pale yellow (
<figureCitation box="[622,728,1735,1761]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="55.[151,250,1875,1899]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,597,1850]" captionTargetId="figure-154@55.[151,1436,597,1852]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURE 29A–E. Patrera longitibialis n. sp. Male (ICN-Ar-5882): A habitus, dorsal view; B left leg, ventral view; C palp, retroventral view; D palp, ventral view; E palp, retrolateral view.Abbreviations: E, embolus; VTP, ventral tegular process. Scale bars: A: B: 1mm; C: 0.5mm; D–E: 0.2mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468447" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468447/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 29A</figureCitation>
). Total length 5.02, carapace length 2.05, width 1.71, high 0.9. Clypeus height 0.07. Eye diameters and interdistances: AME 0.07, ALE 0.11, PME 0.14, PLE 0.14; AME–AME 0.16, AME–ALE 0.24, PME–PME 0.35, PME–PLE 0.34, ALE–PLE 0.29. Chelicerae 0.95 long, three promarginal teeth, six retromarginal teeth. Leg measurements: Leg I—femur 1.95 / patella 0.71/ tibia 2.34/ metatarsus 1.68/ tarsus 0.88/ total 7.58; II—1.76/ 0.7/ 2.07/ 1.46/ 0.71/ 6.71; III—1.33/ 0.51/ 1.08/ 1.37/ 0.52/ 4.83; IV—1.96/ 0.65/ 1.76/ 2.02/ 0.72/ 7.13. Leg spination: I—tibia v2-2-2-2-0, p1-0-1-1, r1-0-1-1, metatarsus v2-2-0-1, p1-1-0-1, r1-1- 0-1; II—tibia v2-2-2-2, p1-1-0-1, r1-0-1-1 (
<figureCitation box="[638,740,1951,1977]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="55.[151,250,1875,1899]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,597,1850]" captionTargetId="figure-154@55.[151,1436,597,1852]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURE 29A–E. Patrera longitibialis n. sp. Male (ICN-Ar-5882): A habitus, dorsal view; B left leg, ventral view; C palp, retroventral view; D palp, ventral view; E palp, retrolateral view.Abbreviations: E, embolus; VTP, ventral tegular process. Scale bars: A: B: 1mm; C: 0.5mm; D–E: 0.2mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468447" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468447/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 29B</figureCitation>
), metatarsus v2-2-0-0, p1-1-0-1, r1-1-0-1; III—tibia d1-0-0-0, v1-2-0-0, p0-1-0-1, r0-0-1-0, metatarsus v2-2-0-0, p1-2-0-2, r1-1-0-2; IV—tibia d1-0-0-0, v1-0-1-0, p1-0-0-1, r1-0- 0-1, metatarsus v2-0-1-1, p1-2-0-2, r1-1-0-2. Abdomen: length 3.16, epigastric furrow 0.76 from tracheal spiracle, spiracle 0.73 from base of spinnerets. Palp: retrolateral tibial apophysis bifid, large, with the ventral branch wider than dorsal branch, which is thin; cymbium longer than tibia; subtegulum longer than wide; tegulum longer than wide, with a strongly sclerotized, wide ventral tegular process closely related to the embolus; median apophysis short, curved and apically situated; embolus short, straight, apically filiform, with narrow base and proximally inserted on the tegulum (
<figureCitation box="[408,490,331,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="55.[151,250,1875,1899]" captionTargetBox="[162,1424,597,1850]" captionTargetId="figure-154@55.[151,1436,597,1852]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURE 29A–E. Patrera longitibialis n. sp. Male (ICN-Ar-5882): A habitus, dorsal view; B left leg, ventral view; C palp, retroventral view; D palp, ventral view; E palp, retrolateral view.Abbreviations: E, embolus; VTP, ventral tegular process. Scale bars: A: B: 1mm; C: 0.5mm; D–E: 0.2mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468447" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468447/files/figure.png" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
C–E).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1436,151,537]" box="[199,418,367,393]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,286,367,393]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Female</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1436,151,537]" box="[199,1358,402,429]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,319,402,428]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Variation.</emphasis>
Males (n=3): total length: 4.99–5.20; carapace length: 2.05–2.73; femur I length: 1.95–2.01.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1436,151,537]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,396,438,465]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Natural History.</emphasis>
The specimens were collected beating on low vegetation, in a protected forest, at a height of 200 meters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
